    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bc81ca40_cc5895d0",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 150,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-21T01:24:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "DelimitedFileReader makes the delimiters optional if it hits EOF.\nIf the delimiters are missing from the other calls, we\u0027ll get a format error when we try to read the next field.\nSince this could be the last character we expect to read from the file, it could be missing and we wouldn\u0027t notice without this check.",
      "parentUuid": "249af639_30627ce3",
      "revId": "f7ccd101a1c0370793694ee82e9ead05b60f7057",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f2421d68_a85c9862",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 160,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-20T14:50:44Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Uh-oh. If there are \\n characters in the path, we’ll either register a format error on the next line or if someone’s particularly crafty and writes a filename with the express purpose of trolling /proc/pid/maps, we’ll pick it up as a real entry.\n\nThe sad thing is that Linux has the ability to escape special characters like \\n (see linux-4.9.23/fs/seq_file.c mangle_path(), which is actually used by seq_file_path(), the function that’s responsible for putting the path in /proc/pid/maps). The usage for /proc/pid/maps just avoids escaping anything.",
      "revId": "f7ccd101a1c0370793694ee82e9ead05b60f7057",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fa7f4502_4449107e",
        "filename": "util/linux/memory_map.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 160,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-04-20T15:08:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e The sad thing\n\nNever mind about that sad thing, I was still looking at task_nommu.c.\n\ntask_mmu.c, which is what we care most about, uses\n\n  seq_file_path(m, file, \"\\n\");\n\nmeaning \"\\n\" will be octal-escaped as \\012.\n\nWe could run this through a decoder for that escape, but stupidly, the encoder doesn‘t escape backslashes, so it’s an ambiguous encoding. So there’s another sad thing that we can’t do anything about, but at least we won’t get trolled.",
      "parentUuid": "f2421d68_a85c9862",
      "revId": "f7ccd101a1c0370793694ee82e9ead05b60f7057",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
